29/1: International information
 1. Why International Organizations Exist at All
International organizations emerged primarily after World War II, when global leaders concluded that uncoordinated nation-states competing economically and militarily had twice destroyed the world, and that some form of permanent cooperation was necessary to reduce conflict, manage trade, stabilize health crises, and rebuild trust.
The core assumption behind these institutions was simple but ambitious:
If countries talk regularly, share rules, and cooperate through institutions, they will be less likely to fight.
However, these organizations were built by states with unequal power, meaning their rules, funding, and enforcement mechanisms often reflected the interests of the strongest members rather than neutral global needs.

3. World Trade Organization (WTO)
History
The WTO was established in 1995, evolving from the post-war General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), with the goal of preventing the protectionist trade wars that contributed to the Great Depression and World War II.
Mission
The WTO aims to promote free trade, reduce tariffs, and provide a rules-based system to resolve trade disputes peacefully rather than through retaliation or war.
What WTO Did Right
• Lowered global tariffs/ import tax 
• Expanded international trade but in wto
• Provided dispute-settlement mechanisms
• Integrated developing economies into global markets
For decades, global trade growth coincided with reduced interstate war.
Major Mistakes and Failures
The WTO assumed that free trade benefits would be evenly distributed, which proved false.

Critics argue it:
• accelerated deindustrialization in some countries very fast - big country  
• weakened labor protections
• struggled to adapt to digital trade and state capitalism
• became paralyzed as major powers ignored rulings

Structural problem:
The WTO has rules, but no real power to enforce them against strong states.
Lesson:
Rules without enforcement work only while everyone believes in them.

