PART 1 READING TEST 711: The Origins of Weather Forecasting
A. The orgirin of the weather forecast
---Aug 1, 1861: First public forecast in The Times -> "General weather probable during next two days" -> started ongoing controversy (people remember failures, not successes).
(First forecast -> Aug 1, 1861 -> The Times -> controversial legacy)
--- Admiral Robert FitzRoy: Head of Meteorological Department -> Britain's "least-known hero" -> brave move because weather prediction = astrology/fortune-telling at the time.
(Robert FitzRoy -> founder of Met Dept -> risky: weather prep seen as a joke/scam) 

B.The Royal Charter Disaster
------ FitzRoy's Background: Faultless reputation -> Captain of HMS Beagle (Charles Darwin's voyage) -> Darwin's Origin of Species connection -> retired Admiral seeking new direction.
(Elite background -> HMS Beagle + Darwin -> retired Navy Admiral)
------ Meteorological Dept: Established June 30, 1854 -> funded by Parliament to chart safe Atlantic routes -> FitzRoy became Chief Statistician -> Government & MPs laughed at the idea of weather reports/forecasts.
(Met Dept 1854 -> goal: safe sailing -> FitzRoy: Chief -> MPs mocked forecasting idea)

C.The Start of Storm Warnings
------ Shift in Focus: Small staff (3 clerks) in London -> FitzRoy bored with transcribing ship reports -> pivoted to preventing loss of life at sea from storms.
(Small office -> bored with data -> priority: saving lives/storm safety)
------ Royal Charter Tragedy (1859): Gale-force winds sank ship near shore -> 430 dead -> national tragedy -> FitzRoy wrote to The Times claiming the storm was predictable.
(1859: Royal Charter disaster -> 430 deaths -> FitzRoy's letter: "this could have been predicted")

D.The Need for Storm Warnings
------ 1859 Fatalities: 1,645 lives lost off British coast -> FitzRoy repeatedly lobbied The Times for a storm-warning service.
(1,645 deaths -> FitzRoy pushed for storm warnings via The Times)
------ Right Timing: Improved weather knowledge + barometer readings -> technological edge: electric telegraph & Morse code (1844) enabled instant communication.
(Perfect timing -> better science + barometers -> telegraph/Morse code = instant data)

E.FitzRoy’s Weather Forecast Service
------ Feb 1861 Innovation: Storm-warning service launched -> standardized instruments for accuracy -> telegraph reports sent daily at fixed times -> detailed weather maps created.
(Storm warnings -> standardized gear -> daily telegraph data -> maps)
------ Safety System: Warnings telegraphed to ports -> flag system hoisted for ships -> lives lost fell by 1/3 (biggest advance since lifeboats) -> FitzRoy became a maritime hero.
(Port flags -> saved lives -> deaths down 33% -> hero to sailors)
------ Public Forecasts: Daily service in The Times (Aug 1861) -> huge attention (including Queen Victoria) -> popular with fishermen (safety) but disliked by vessel owners (delays/lost money).
(Aug 1861 public launch -> Royal interest -> workers happy vs. owners angry at delays)

F.Problems with Early Forecasts
------ Challenges & Backlash: Weather forecasting was technically difficult -> one error led to bad publicity -> inaccurate forecasts triggered "heated correspondence" in The Times.
(Hard to predict -> mistakes = public outcry -> letters of complaint)

G.The Legacy of Weather Forecasting
------ Modern Recognition: FitzRoy was ahead of his time -> now honored as a "towering figure" -> sea area renamed "FitzRoy" in the official shipping forecast.
(Late recognition -> meteorology giant -> sea area namesake)
------ Sacrifice & Legacy: Determination cost his health (died prematurely) -> published a pioneering book on forecasting -> recognized by scientists as a masterpiece of early science.
(Personal cost -> premature death -> book legacy -> scientific validation)

